New Features of timetrash
1. Debugging in the style of Bash's -v option:
   (1) For each command tree, Bash outputs the entire command before its execution;
   (2) Bash also outputs comments from "#...".
   (3) Print line number of commands
2. Debugging in the style of Bash's -x option:
   (1) Bash outputs every single command before its execution;
   (2) Bash provides informative description for each executed command. 
      If the description of a command exists within our database,
      Bash will output that corresponding description "(command info: ...)".
      If it is not found,
      Bash will output ¡°(please try the manual page for more info...)¡±



Examples:
Shell script in mytest.sh:
echo hello && pwd # -v option can print out comments 

--------------------------------------------------------------
case 1 (regular):
$ ./timetrash mytest.sh
hello
/w/home.06/class/classkex/111/lab1design
--------------------------------------------------------------

--------------------------------------------------------------
case 2 (-v option):
$ ./timetrash -v mytest.sh
echo hello && pwd -v option can print out comments
hello
/w/home.06/class/classkex/111/lab1design
--------------------------------------------------------------

--------------------------------------------------------------
case (-x option):
$ ./timetrash -x mytest.sh
+ echo hello (command info: display a line of text)
hello
+ pwd (command info: print name of current/working directory)
/w/home.06/class/classkex/111/lab1design
--------------------------------------------------------------